},
"children":[
{
"type":"section",
"id":"mk19_bb_nr_s16_1",
"title":{
"__html":"Diagnosis"
},
"titleNode":{
"type":"section-title",
"hlId":"523223",
"children":[
"Diagnosis"
]
},
"children":[
{
"type":"p",
"hlId":"de77b9",
"children":[
"Patients with neuropathy may present with pain, paresthesias, weakness, or autonomic dysfunction. Neuropathies may be classified by:"
]
},
{
"type":"list",
"children":[
" ",
{
"type":"list-item",
"hlId":"55fd3e",
"children":[
"distribution of sensorimotor deficits (symmetric vs asymmetric, distal vs proximal, focal vs generalized)"
]
},
" ",
{
"type":"list-item",
"hlId":"d05b95",
"children":[
"pathology (demyelinating vs axonal)"
]
},
" ",
{
"type":"list-item",
"hlId":"8af9b2",
"children":[
"size of nerve fibers involved (large vs small fibers)"
]
},
" ",
{
"type":"list-item",
"hlId":"ffb1da",
"children":[
"family history"
]
},
" ",
{
"type":"list-item",
"hlId":"491c9b",
"children":[
"autonomic involvement"
]
},
" "
]
},
{
"type":"p",
"hlId":"0d01ed",
"children":[
"Mononeuropathies, isolated disorders affecting a single peripheral nerve, are most frequently caused by nerve entrapment or compression (carpal tunnel syndrome)."
]
},
{
"type":"p",
"hlId":"ca7382",
"children":[
"Mononeuropathy multiplex involves several noncontiguous peripheral nerves, either simultaneously or sequentially. It is often the result of vasculitis or a systemic disease."
]
},
{
"type":"p",
"hlId":"240f2c",
"children":[
"Polyneuropathy refers to a diffuse, generalized, and usually symmetric peripheral neuropathy. ",
{
"type":"alert",
"children":[
"Polyneuropathy is often a manifestation of systemic disease (e.g., diabetes, vitamin B",
{
"type":"tag",
"tagName":"sub",
"attrs":{
},
"children":[
"12"
]
},
" deficiency) or exposure to a toxin (e.g., alcohol) or medication (e.g., chemotherapy)."
]
}
]
},
{
"type":"p",
"hlId":"e287fb",
"children":[
{
"type":"abbreviation",
"title":"electromyography",
"children":[
"EMG"
]
},
" and nerve conduction velocity may be helpful in characterizing the type (axonal or demyelinating), severity, and distribution of the disease. Other routine tests include vitamin B",
{
"type":"tag",
"tagName":"sub",
"attrs":{
},
"children":[
"12"
]
},
" level, ",
{
"type":"no-wrap",
"children":[
{
"type":"abbreviation",
"title":"serum protein electrophoresis",
"children":[
"SPEP"
]
},
","
]
},
" ",
{
"type":"no-wrap",
"children":[
{
"type":"abbreviation",
"title":"urine protein electrophoresis",
"children":[
"UPEP"
]
},
","
]
},
" ",
{
"type":"no-wrap",
"children":[
{
"type":"abbreviation",
"title":"erythrocyte sedimentation rate",
"children":[
"ESR"
]
},
","
]
},
" hemoglobin A",
{
"type":"tag",
"tagName":"sub",
"attrs":{
},
"children":[
"1c"
]
},
", and fasting blood glucose level."
]
},
{
"type":"inline-wrap",
"wrapId":"1",
"contentIds":[
"mk19_bb_nr_s16_inline_t1"
],
"forceOpen":true
}
]
},
{
"type":"section",
"id":"mk19_bb_nr_s16_2",
"title":{
"__html":"Treatment"
},
"titleNode":{
"type":"section-title",
"hlId":"4c4ac0",
"children":[
"Treatment"
]
},
"children":[
{
"type":"p",
"hlId":"498465",
"children":[
"Only pregabalin, duloxetine, and tapentadol (extended release) are FDA approved for the treatment of painful neuropathy."
]
},
{
"type":"heading",
"class":"tricked",
"children":[
"Don't Be Tricked"
]
},
{
"type":"list",
"class":"tricked",
"children":[
" ",
{
"type":"list-item",
"hlId":"035050",
"children":[
"When the presentation of Bell palsy is classic and without any additional neurologic deficits, brain imaging and routine laboratory testing are not necessary."
]
},
" ",
{
"type":"list-item",
"hlId":"0a9302",
"children":[
"Do not treat Bell palsy with antiviral drugs."
]
},
" ",
{
"type":"list-item",
"hlId":"cadb21",
"children":[
"Screening for glucose intolerance should be performed in all nondiabetic patients who have distal sensory neuropathy."
]
},
" ",
{
"type":"list-item",
"hlId":"248abe",
"children":[
"Glucocorticoids are not beneficial in Guillain-Barré syndrome and may even slow the recovery."
]
},
" "
]
}
]
},
{
"type":"section",
"id":"mk19_bb_nr_s16_3",
"title":{
"__html":"Test Yourself"
},
"titleNode":{
"type":"section-title",
"hlId":"7866cc",
"children":[
"Test Yourself"
]
},
"children":[
{
"type":"p",
"hlId":"b365e8",
"class":"test",
"children":[
"A 37-year-old woman has difficulty going up stairs. She had diarrhea and low-grade fever 2 weeks ago. Physical examination shows weakness of both lower extremities and diminished deep tendon reflexes."
]
},
{
"type":"p",
"hlId":"ab5306",
"class":"test_answer",
"children":[
{
"type":"tag",
"tagName":"b",
"attrs":{
},
"children":[
"Answer:"
]
},
" ",
"For diagnosis, choose Guillain-Barré syndrome. For management, select plasma exchange and IV immune globulin."
]
}
]
}
]
},
